\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hall effect is the effect that we observe when we add a magnetic field
 to a sample while current it driven through it.
 The magnetic field induce a force that will tend to move up positive charges
 and pull down negative charges.
 The separation of charges (
\color red
pilled up at the suface? 
\color inherit
) in the conductor will create a electric field and potential.
 The resulting potential difference is calld the Hall voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{H}$
\end_inset

.
 The Hall effect can be quantify by various parameters.
 The Hall coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{H}=\frac{E_{y}}{J_{x}B}=\frac{V_{H}d}{IB}=\frac{1}{ne}$
\end_inset

, where (
\color red
tabulate and refer to the appendix ? 
\color inherit
) 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{y}$
\end_inset

 is the magnitude of the electric field created by the charge pile-up, 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the current density in the sample, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the magnitude of the magnetic field, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the thickness of the sample (in a case of a rectangular, perpendiculat
 to field chip), 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the charge carrier density and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

is the electronic charge.
 Another way of quantifying the hall effect is the Hall angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{H}$
\end_inset

 defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{H}=\frac{V_{y}}{V_{x}}=\frac{E_{y}w}{E_{x}l}=\frac{w}{l}\mu_{H}B$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the Hall voltage drop accross a width 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 on the sample, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 is the voltage drop acroos a length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 on the sample, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{x}$
\end_inset

 are corresponding electric fields, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{H}$
\end_inset

 is the mobility, where the mobility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 of a charge carrier is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{\sigma}{ne}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\nicefrac{1}{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is the conductivity of the material (inverse of the resistivity).
 
\end_layout

